 through activism, artisanship, and performance. This musical representation of indigeneity not only helps shape contemporary culture, it also provides a lens through which to reflect on the country’s past. Tucker argues that by following the musicians that have championed chimaycha music in its many forms, we can trace shifting meanings of indigeneity—and indeed, uncover the ways it is constructed, transformed, and ultimately recreated through music.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aIndians of South AmericazPeruzCangallo (Province)vMusicxHistory and criticism. 0aIndians of South AmericazPeruzCangallo (Province)xMusicxHistory and criticism. 0aIndians of South AmericazPeruzCangallo (Province)xSocial life and customs. 0aIndians of South AmericazPeruzCangallo (Province)xSocial life andcustoms. 0aPopular musiczPeruzCangallo (Province)xHistory and criticism. 0aSongs, QuechuazPeruzCangallo (Province)xHistory and criticism. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh  aAndes.  aEcology.  aIndigenous Peoples.  aMaterial Culture.  aMusic.  aMusical Instruments.  aPeru.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Stud. 2019 Englishz978311061036908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Studies 2019z9783110606348oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z97831107119430 cprintz978022660716040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226607474423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226607474/original  a978-3-1